1582525800.title: Father Brown
1582525800.descr: Father Brown is a Catholic priest and an amateur detective solving murder cases, set during the 1950s in the fictional village Kembleford in Cotswold area, England. He uses his own wits as well as skills of his close friends, and being a priest allows him to look straight to the truth. He is strongly against the capital punishment for the capital crimes, as still applied in Britain of that time.

1582528500.title: Fawlty Towers
1582528500.descr: Classic British sitcom starring John Cleese, which revolves around Basil Fawlty and his wife Sybil, owners and managers of a seaside hotel, as they attempt to raise the standard of their place, with often disastrous results. Basil's short-temper and a proneness to anger outbursts, combined with his socially conservative upringing, are the main source of comedy.

1582530300.title: DIY SOS: The Big Build
1582530300.descr: Take a family in desperate need of help in their home. Add some local tradesmen, lot's of generosity and a bucket load of community spirit. You've got yourself the recipe for DIY SOS. Nick Knowles, along with him team of home improvement experts, and lot's of happy volunteers from the communities of Britain pitch in to make life changing modifications to the homes of families who need them most.

1582572600.title: EastEnders
1582572600.descr: Albert Square, a traditional Victorian square of terrace houses surrounding a park in the East End is home to many families and is a place where romance, jealousy, domestic rivalry, gossip and extramarital affairs are regularly featured. This "slice of life" series, broadcasted since 1985, follows the stories of local residents and their families and their dilemmas.

1582580400.title: Back
1582580400.descr: After discovering Andrew has been left a share of the business in Laurie's will, he and Stephen clash about how to clear the pub's debts.

1582581900.title: Uncle
1582581900.descr: Andy's creative juices are flowing and he's gathering a measure of success as a music producer. For the first time, he has to think about real decisions regarding what matters most to him, family or career: can he prioritise his career without hurting his relationship with his family? And what about settling down and having his own family? Can he be happy as a successful writer/producer, even if it means he'll never be a "star?" Can he be a successful star if it might preclude a wife and kids? Errol is dealing with disillusionment and stability changes in his two new home lives. He's always put a priority on education and school but now it's losing its luster. He's looking for more from life, he's looking for meaning and being the smartest guy in the room's not doing it for him anymore, especially as hormones start to kick in.

1582583700.title: From Darkness
1582583700.descr: A direct threat to Claire's life brings her increasingly close to John, but sends her running home to the Western Isles. However, Norrie then sends her to Manchester, where she realises she must solve the case. Meanwhile, John faces pressure from the ambitious DSI Keir.

1582587000.title: From Darkness
1582587000.descr: Claire's confession and a disastrous attempt to capture the prime suspect results in John's suspension. DSI Keir takes over the case and Claire is forced to manipulate Lucy Maxley in order to stop the killing and find the culprit.
